# JavaScript Syntax

JavaScript syntax refers to the set of rules used to write JavaScript programs correctly. It defines how statements,
variables, functions, operators, and other elements are written and organized in code. JavaScript is a case-sensitive
language, which means variables like `name` and `Name` are treated as different identifiers. Every JavaScript statement 
is usually written line by line and can end with a semicolon, although semicolons are optional in many cases. JavaScript
code can be written directly inside HTML using the `<script>` tag or in separate `.js` files. Curly braces `{}` are used
to define blocks of code such as loops and functions. Comments are also part of syntax and are used to explain code for 
better readability. Single-line comments use `//` while multi-line comments use `/* */`. JavaScript supports keywords like
`var`, `let`, `const`, `if`, `for`, and `function` which have special meanings in the language. Correct syntax is important
because even a small mistake can generate errors and stop the program from executing properly. JavaScript syntax forms the 
foundation for creating interactive and dynamic web applications.

